      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">A 6-month-old infant is brought to a pediatric ophthalmology clinic with enlarged and cloudy corneas, excessive tearing, and light sensitivity. Examination reveals increased intraocular pressure, corneal edema, and increased cup:disc ratio of the optic nerve head. The diagnosis of developmental glaucoma (congenital glaucoma) is made. All of the following drugs can be given to lower the IOP except?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3113361",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31285,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        8
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. C) Brimonidine</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">Brimonidine is an <strong>alpha-agonist</strong> that <strong>reduces</strong> the <strong>production</strong> of <strong>aqueous humour</strong> and <strong>increases aqueous outflow </strong>via <strong>uveoscleral pathway</strong>.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">It can <strong>cross blood-brain barrier</strong> and cause <strong>drowsiness</strong> and <strong>respiratory depression</strong> in <strong>infants</strong> and <strong>children</strong> and is therefore <strong>contraindicated</strong> in them.</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A. Dorzolamide&nbsp;</strong>is a <strong>topical carbonic anhydrase inhibitor</strong> that <strong>decreases aqueous humour production</strong>. It is generally considered <strong>safe</strong> and can be used in <strong>infants</strong> to <strong>lower IOP</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B. Latanoprost,&nbsp;</strong>a <strong>prostaglandin analogue</strong> used to <strong>increase</strong> the <strong>outflow</strong> of <strong>aqueous humour</strong>, thereby <strong>lowering IOP</strong>. It is <strong>generally safe</strong> for use in <strong>infants</strong>, although <strong>monitoring</strong> for <strong>potential side effects</strong> like iris hyperpigmentation is important.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D. Betaxolol&nbsp;</strong>is a <strong>beta-blocker</strong> used in <strong>glaucoma</strong> to <strong>reduce aqueous humour production</strong>. It is <strong>generally safe</strong> for use in <strong>infants</strong>, although, like <strong>all systemic beta-blockers</strong>, it <strong>requires monitoring</strong> for <strong>potential respiratory</strong> and <strong>cardiovascular effects</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective</u></strong>:</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Brimonidine</strong>, an <strong>alpha-2 adrenergic agonist</strong> that <strong>reduces aqueous humour production</strong> and <strong>increases uveoscleral outflow</strong>, is not recommended for use in infants and young children due to the <strong>risk</strong> of <strong>severe side effects</strong>, <strong>including respiratory problems</strong>, <strong>lethargy</strong>, and <strong>decreased heart rate</strong>. It is <strong>contraindicated</strong> in <strong>children</strong> under the <strong>age of 2 years</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Ref:&nbsp;</u>Parsons Diseases of Eye 22<sup>nd</sup> Edition Page: 157</strong></span></p>",
